05342nam a22007095i 9780226579597DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20182018ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2018017410  a9780226579597  a(DE-B1597)524138  a(OCoLC)1054093023  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aHG2529b.L66 2018 4aHG2529b.L66 2019 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a346.0822231 aLomazoff, Eric, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aReconstructing the National Bank Controversy :bPolitics and Law in the Early American Republic /cEric Lomazoff. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b2 line drawings, 3 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Getting the Ship out of the Bottle -- tChapter One. Varieties of Strict Interpretation -- tChapter Two. “Banco Mania” and Institutional Drift -- tChapter Three. “The Great Regulating Wheel” and Institutional Conversion -- tChapter Four. More Than a Constitutional Rerun -- tChapter Five. The Compromise of 1816 -- tChapter Six. McCulloch (1819) in the Shadow of the Compromise -- tChapter Seven. A Tale of Two Clauses -- tConclusion. A Revisionist Bank Narrative–Lessons Timely and Timeless -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Bank of the United States sparked several rounds of intense debate over the meaning of the Constitution’s Necessary and Proper Clause, which authorizes the federal government to make laws that are “necessary” for exercising its other powers. Our standard account of the national bank controversy, however, is incomplete. The controversy was much more dynamic than a two-sided debate over a single constitutional provision and was shaped as much by politics as by law. With Reconstructing the National Bank Controversy, Eric Lomazoff offers a far more robust account of the constitutional politics of national banking between 1791 and 1832. During that time, three forces—changes within the Bank itself, growing tension over federal power within the Republican coalition, and the endurance of monetary turmoil beyond the War of 1812 —drove the development of our first major debate over the scope of federal power at least as much as the formal dimensions of the Constitution or the absence of a shared legal definition for the word “necessary.” These three forces—sometimes alone, sometimes in combination—repeatedly reshaped the terms on which the Bank’s constitutionality was contested. Lomazoff documents how these three dimensions of the polity changed over time and traces the manner in which they periodically led federal officials to adjust their claims about the Bank’s constitutionality. This includes the emergence of the Coinage Clause—which gives Congress power to “coin money, regulate the value thereof”—as a novel justification for the institution. He concludes the book by explaining why a more robust account of the national bank controversy can help us understand the constitutional basis for modern American monetary politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aBank of the United States (1791-1811)-History. 0aBank of the United States (1816-1836)-History. 0aBanking lawzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aBanking law-United States-History-19th century. 0aConstitutional historyzUnited States. 0aConstitutional history-United States. 0aLawxPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aLaw-Political aspects-United States-History-19th century. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aAmerican political development.  aBank of the United States.  aCoinage Clause.  aDemocratic-Republi